Young women over the past 10 years in Somaliland have transformed an escalating epidemic of teenage and illegal childbirth into an actively organized movement to sanction their sexual and reproductive expression, seeking the knowledge they need to facilitate sexual education in their community, and to plan for voluntary family planning once obtaining an education past grade five. According to one aid agency, “The first thing they want is education. The second is family planning.” They also seek legal reform of Somaliland laws that perpetuate their oppression.

Promoting sexual and reproductive health and rights information should not be limited to the issue of contraceptives, unplanned pregnancy, and sexually transmitted diseases. We should work with Somaliland partners to address sexual violence and to promote diverse self-conceptions of sexuality.

Support more research on sexual and reproductive health and rights in Somaliland, especially among marginalized populations and in the media.

Violence against women and girls remains one of the most widespread human rights abuses in Somaliland. Rape is the second most common violent crime in the country after murder, characterized by one Somaliland NGO as a “national epidemic.” Because of cultural norms which consider virginity synonymous with chastity, women and girls are vehemently discouraged from reporting rapes to authorities and are often harassed and persecuted for publicly reporting rapes.
